🎄If you’re looking for a last minute allergy free dessert, look no further! This was so easy to make that I concocted it while playing with Baby Rapini in his high chair.🎄 Top 8 free and gluten free. 

🎄1/2 bag allergy free dark chocolate chips
🎄 1 bag allergy free semi sweet chocolate chips
🎄 a dash of pure vanilla extract 
🎄 the juice of one orange
🎄 1/3 cup @sunbutter 
🎄 1/2 cup vegan butter or solid coconut oil 
🎄 1 box of allergy free crunchy cookies, whatever flavour you prefer

Fill a small saucepan halfway with water and bring to a simmer. Add all of the ingredients, except the cookies, to a medium mixing bowl and place over the heating water. Stir often to melt and combine the ingredients. Once fully melted, remove from the heat. 
Smash the cookies into crumbs and lay then put in your serving dish. Any 8 inch serving dish or baking tray will work. 
Pour the mixture over top and smooth it out evenly. Cover with plastic wrap or parchment. Refrigerate for a half hour - 45 minutes, or until just slightly firm. If you refrigerate for too long it will harden too much. 

Cut into slices and serve. 
.
.

In 2021 I was losing my mind. No sane person should be gardening as much as I gardened that year. I couldn’t believe how quick people were to dismiss me because I was “too niche”, as though a shot of a beautiful plate of food doesn’t appeal to everyone, or as though I wasn’t able to wear gloves and a mask if needed. One person even told me I should not even bother trying to get a “normal” client, it wasn’t going to happen. I’d have amazing discovery calls that ended with “but I guess you’ll always have the perspective of an allergy person though?”. But it was all okay. I had to be patient. I had to stop and reassess my strategy. And then suddenly a “normal” publisher reached out to me to produce a food allergy cookbook because they felt it was a huge market with lots of room for content. Then a publisher from France asked me to contribute to a Thermomix cookbook because they wanted a genuine perspective from someone with food allergies. 2022 has been an incredible year. Thanks to @carineredmondvarty for seeing my vision, not dismissing me, and connecting me with the right opportunities in mainstream media. Now that the ball is rolling, I’m just getting started. I feel embraced. Launching @freetobemeevents is one of my proudest achievements this year. It’s an event for US, a room full of people who JUST GET IT. The sky is the limit and I can’t wait to see what 2023 holds. Thank you to all of you for being here with me 🙏💕 every time I get a kind word of encouragement, it means so much. Happy new year 🥳

I felt inspired to do a then vs now post thanks to @livingkitchenco . 
When I started blogging about my life with food allergies in 2015, I was a 24 year old who was coming to terms with not growing out of it. My blog was called Amanda’s Recipes, for the first year. I was navigating office life, going out on the weekends, dating Brandon, and dealing with a gargantuan amount of food anxiety due to my history of anaphylaxis, and my first cookbook was coming out that spring. I shared my first book signing at a library conference, my complicated feelings about being an adult with a disease that was perceived as a children’s issue (at the time), and also shared really fun book reviews that my friend and I did in my kitchen (that’s how how my kitchen used to look!!). The blog evolved so much over the years and I’m grateful to everyone who has stuck around to see the change. Planning an allergy friendly wedding, getting married, blowing up my life and suddenly leaving my job, starting a short-lived e-shop, finally dealing with my anxiety after a total breakdown, working on my disordered eating issues, starting a YouTube channel, getting pregnant, more books, baby Rapini, @freetobemeevents , entering the TV world… EVERYTHING. I have shared nearly my whole adult life here, with you. Allergy life never gets easier, it just changes with every new phase of life. Thank you for being here and for your support through it all 💕💕
.

🫒☕️When I heard Starbucks was coming out with an olive oil based line of coffee, I was intrigued. Coffee and olive oil are two of my favourite things. I’ll admit that part of my brain panicked at the thought of further straining the olive industry. These are the things I worry about 😆 but then I moved on to trying it at home. Any oil blended at high speed with a hot coffee will become creamy. Now that you know that, go forth and create! I used two shots of brewed espresso, 1 tbsp olive oil, 1/2 tsp pure vanilla extract, and 1 tsp raw sugar. Blend on high until it becomes visibly creamy. Add a dash of cinnamon at the end if you wish. WE ALL MISTAKES I have been walking around with an Epi in my purse, that expired in September 2022. I used to be more organized and on point, but I’m learning to balance allergy-adulting and mom-ing. There are a lot more little things on my mind these days as I’m also taking care of someone other than myself. Before we went to Banff, I popped in to Shoppers Drug Mart to grab some baby food pouches and thought to check my Epi’s as I was passing the pharmacy counter. Wouldn’t you know it, one was expired. I immediately handed it over to the pharmacist and asked for a new one. He thought I needed a Jr. but nope - it was for myself! I was annoyed at myself for having let my Epi expire, but made a mental note for next time. I usually have a calendar notification set but it seems I had forgotten that too. Thankfully, I got it sorted before we left.

Do you have that one thing that you’re nervous to try, but that you want to try, so you keep buying it and not trying it? It put me off dairy free cheese alternatives for the rest of my life, until I found nutritional yeast and started warming up to that idea. And TBH this is why I rarely buy pre-made plant milks anymore 😅 As a kid, plant milks were mostly just for people with dietary issues, or the few vegans out there, and I had a brand that I was very confident in and trusted for probably 20 years. Oat milk had not yet been perfected and was a watery concoction that I used for baking. When plant milks got crazy popular and so many new options were added, like different nut and legume milks, I started to lose trust as companies were unable to tell me how (or even IF) they cleaned after legume milks were made, and co-packers were producing so many milks in one place. It got murky (loll). I felt I had been pushed out of my niche. I much prefer to make my own oat and rice milk now, and have made some YouTube videos about it on my channel. The days of coming home from school and pouring a giant glass of vanilla rice milk to sip while watching Relic Hunter are behind me. Maybe I should launch my 2019 spoof brand, Squeezed Plants, for real?!?

Cinnamon Spread Dupe 🍞
Who remembers good ole cinnamon spread? It was refined soy oil (I could have it!), sugar, flavours, and a bunch of random preservative-type stuff. DELISH 😂 I loved this growing up. It was an amazing alternative to butter on my toast in the morning. Here’s how I make my faux version, since this great stuff has sadly been discontinued. 
✨ 1/4 cup refined solid coconut oil (not extra virgin!) or your favourite vegan butter spread 
✨ 1/8 tsp sea salt
✨ 1/4 tsp ground cinnamon 
✨ 1/4 tsp ground Ceylon cinnamon 
✨ a splash of pure vanilla extract 
✨ 1 tsp raw sugar
Mix it up really well! Then spread it on toast. I’m still working on a version that can live in the fridge but in the meantime, make this one to order!

Listen, there are lots of ways to get your recommended calcium intake. I’m not a nutritionist but these are the ways I get calcium in my daily diet.
- tinned sardines and salmon - with the bones in 
- blackstrap molasses
- dark leafy greens, like dinosaur kale 
- growing up, I took calcium chews or pills, and drank enriched rice milk or enriched juice.
If you see a dairy milk that says “fortified” that means vitamins or other nutrients have been added to it too. I think it’s a common misconception that dairy is healthier than any other milk, but if you’re allergic to dairy like I am, there are lots of options to boost your calcium intake 💕 my fat intake on the other hand… that’s an ongoing challenge 😆
